        <productionVolumeComment xml:lang="en">Estimated value. The European production volume is extrapolated from the global production volume using the nominal GDP of 2010 (source: United Nations, http://data.un.org/Glossary.aspx?q=GDP+%28current+US%24%29, accessed 20130726 and 20130312).

Comment from GLO dataset: Gross domestic product (GDP) at current prices is GDP at prices of the current reporting period. Also known as nominal GDP.The global total production of C&amp;D waste is estimated to be 325 million tonnes in 2003 (http://www3.epa.gov/epawaste/inforesources/pubs/infocus/rif-cd.pdf, accessed 20151013). To calculate the share that is redirected to inert material landfill, sanitary landfill and recycling the weighted average (based on nominal GDP, source: United Nations, http://data.un.org/Glossary.aspx?q=GDP+%28current+US%24%29, accessed 20130726 and 20130312) of treatments in EU (GDP2005 0.330592), Honk Kong (GDP2005 0.003972) and Northeast America (GDP2005 0.274857) is calculated. Honk Kong’s Environmental protection department reports 95% of construction waste to inert material landfill and 5% to landfill (Statistic unit, 2013) (https://www.wastereduction.gov.hk/sites/default/files/msw2013.pdf, accessed 20151013). US Northeast Waste Management Officials’ Association reports 70% of waste going to inert material landfill and 30% to landfill (2009) (http://www.newmoa.org/solidwaste/CDReport2006DataFinalJune302009.pdf, accessed 20151013). For the EU, treatments vary greatly between states (recycling varies from less than 10% to over 90%) as an average 90% of waste is sent to inert material landfill and 10% to recycling. The weighted average of these regions result in 81% of waste sent to inert material landfill, 14% to sanitary landfill and 5% to recycling. No dataset for recycling is available at the moment.</productionVolumeComment>
